<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06270003 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06270003 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  COMPUTER; ELECTRONICS; COMPANY; JAPAN  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Tandy Corp. on Wednesday announced a joint venture with Matsushita ElectricIndustrial Corp. to manufacture lap-top and notebook computers in Fort Worth.;  Tandy and Matsushita will be equal partners in a company -- to be calledPTCC Inc. -- that will make computers in a now-vacant 62,000-square-foot Tandyfactory.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  TANDY, MATSUSHITA PLAN COMPUTER VENTURE  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The new company, expected to begin computer production in February, is toemploy about 100 people, said Tandy Chairman and CEO John Roach.;   Theventure provides Matsushita, which sells products under the Panasonic, Quasarand Technics brands, the opportunity to domestically produce more of theproducts it sells here.;   It will help Tandy to compete more effectively inthe changing lap-top market, Roach said.;   &quot;It's a very competitive, verydevelopment intensive, very technologically driven business,&quot; Roach said. &quot;Weboth have attributes that can contribute to all these phases.&quot;;   Bothcompanies will license their proprietary technology to the joint venturecompany. Any technologies developed by PTTC will be shared by the two firms.;  Lap-tops manufactured by PTTC will be sold under the Panasonic, Tandy, Gridand Victor names.;   In 1988, Tandy signed an agreement to manufacturecomputers that Matsushita sells under its Panasonic brand name. That agreementwill not be affected by the new joint venture.;   The market for lap-topcomputers is becoming an increasingly competitive and price-sensitive field ofthe industry, said Bruce Stephen, director of personal computer hardwareresearch at International Data Corp. in Framingham, Mass. &quot;This has become acommodity market very quickly,&quot; he said.;   Stephen estimates the prices ofsome lap-top computer models have dropped more than 25 percent in the pastyear because of increased competition.;   More than 1.1 million lap-top andnotebook computers will be sold in the United States this year, generatingrevenues of $3.2 billion, according to International Data.;   By 1995, morethan 2.3 million lap-top and notebook computers will be sold, generatingindustry sales of $5 billion, according to the research firm.;   Bryce Drake,now Tandy's general manager of computer manufacturing, will be the presidentof the new venture. Takashi Himi, a 20-year veteran of Matsushita, will beexecutive vice president.;   At full capacity, the new PTCC factory would beable to make 10,000 personal computers a month. Roach said he expects thefacility to be at full capacity by next September.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Fort Worth Star-Telegram  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Fort Worth, Texas  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910926  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  2C  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  389  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday, September 26, 199100270003,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>